   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Stars twinkle because of **Earth’s atmosphere**. This phenomenon is scientifically known as **atmospheric scintillation**.\n",
      "\n",
      "Here is the step-by-step breakdown of why it happens:\n",
      "\n",
      "### 1. Stars are \"Point Sources\"\n",
      "Stars are incredibly far away from Earth. Because of this distance, they appear to us as tiny, single points of light. Even though they are giant spheres of gas, they are so distant that the light coming from them arrives as a narrow, concentrated beam.\n",
      "\n",
      "### 2. The Atmosphere is Turbulent\n",
      "The air surrounding Earth isn't a steady, still block. It is made up of different layers with varying:\n",
      "*   **Temperatures:** Warm air rises and cold air sinks.\n",
      "*   **Densities:** Some pockets of air are thicker than others.\n",
      "*   **Wind currents:** Air is constantly moving and swirling.\n",
      "\n",
      "### 3. Refraction (The Bending of Light)\n",
      "As the beam of starlight enters our atmosphere, it passes through these different layers of air. When light moves from one density of air to another, it **refracts**, meaning it bends slightly.\n",
      "\n",
      "Because the air is constantly moving and shifting, the light beam is bent in different directions many times per second. To your eye, this makes the star appear to:\n",
      "*   Shift slightly in position.\n",
      "*   Change in brightness.\n",
      "*   Change slightly in color.\n",
      "\n",
      "**This rapid shifting is what we perceive as \"twinkling.\"**\n",
      "\n",
      "---\n",
      "\n",
      "### Fun Fact: Why don't planets twinkle?\n",
      "You may have noticed that some bright objects in the sky (like Venus, Mars, or Jupiter) glow with a steady light. This is because planets are much closer to Earth than stars are. \n",
      "\n",
      "Instead of being a \"point source,\" a planet appears as a **tiny disk**. While the light from the edge of the disk is twinkling, the light from the other side is twinkling in a different direction. These opposite movements cancel each other out, resulting in a steady, non-twinkling light.\n",
      "\n",
      "**Pro Tip:** If you see a bright light in the sky and you aren't sure if it's a star or a planet, watch it closely. **If it twinkles, it's a star; if it's steady, it's likely a planet.**\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "response = ollama.generate(\n",
